# Complete Implementation

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <cstring>
#include <cstddef>

using namespace hexi::detail;

bool check_regions_overlap(const void* src, std::size_t src_len, const void* dst, std::size_t dst_len) {
    // Handle null pointers or zero-length regions
    if (!src || !dst || src_len == 0 || dst_len == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // Convert pointers to byte pointers for arithmetic
    const auto* src_start = static_cast<const unsigned char*>(src);
    const auto* src_end = src_start + src_len;
    const auto* dst_start = static_cast<const unsigned char*>(dst);
    const auto* dst_end = dst_start + dst_len;

    // Two regions overlap if:
    // src_start is before dst_end AND dst_start is before src_end
    // This covers all overlap cases including partial and complete overlaps
    return (src_start < dst_end) && (dst_start < src_end);
}

bool safe_memory_copy(void* destination, const void* source, std::size_t length) {
    // Validate input parameters
    if (!destination || !source) {
        return false;
    }

    // Zero-length copy is a successful no-op
    if (length == 0) {
        return true;
    }

    // Check if source and destination regions overlap
    if (check_regions_overlap(source, length, destination, length)) {
        // Regions overlap - use memmove which safely handles overlapping memory
        std::memmove(destination, source, length);
    } else {
        // No overlap - safe to use memcpy (potentially more efficient)
        std::memcpy(destination, source, length);
    }

    return true;
}
```

## Explanation:

**`check_regions_overlap` function:**
- First checks for null pointers or zero-length regions (which don't overlap)
- Converts void pointers to byte pointers for proper arithmetic
- Calculates the end addresses of both regions
- Uses the standard overlap formula: two ranges [A, B) and [C, D) overlap if A < D AND C < B

**`safe_memory_copy` function:**
- Validates input parameters (null checks)
- Treats zero-length copy as a successful operation
- Checks for region overlap using the `check_regions_overlap` function
- If overlap is detected, uses `std::memmove` which safely handles overlapping regions
- If no overlap, uses `std::memcpy` which may be more efficient but requires non-overlapping regions
- Returns `true` on success, `false` on invalid input

This implementation ensures memory safety by detecting overlaps and using the appropriate copy function.

